# Known Logic Analyzer Configurations

Copy this file to `CONFIGS.md` and fill in your own LA wiring per
transport/chip. `CONFIGS.md` is gitignored — it describes one person's bench
setup (which LA channel clips onto which pin), not a repo-wide fact, so it
never gets committed. This file is the template: decoder id, decoder channel
names, and default samplerate are the same for everyone and stay filled in
here once known; only the LA-channel-to-pin wiring is per-bench and belongs
in `CONFIGS.md`.

See `sigrok/PROBING.md` for how to use these configs.

Filled in on request, transport/chip by transport/chip.

## Transports

### I2C

- Decoder: `i2c` (built-in)
- Decoder channels: `scl`, `sda`
- Samplerate: `250k` is sufficient for standard/fast-mode I2C
- Trigger: `sda=f` (SDA falling edge) — matches an I2C START condition, so
  the capture begins right as a transaction starts instead of on idle bus
- Capture command template (fill in your LA channel wiring from `CONFIGS.md`):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -d fx2lafw \
    --channels <ch_sda>=SDA,<ch_scl>=SCL \
    --config samplerate=250k:captureratio=1 \
    --triggers SDA=f \
    --output-file i2c.sr \
    --time <duration>
  ```
  `<duration>` is the approximate runtime of the test/example being probed —
  the trigger positions the capture at the transaction, `--time` just bounds
  the session.
- Analyze command (channel names come from the capture, no `-C` needed):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -i i2c.sr -P i2c:scl=SCL:sda=SDA -A i2c
  ```

### SPI

- Decoder: `spi` (built-in)
- Decoder channels: `clk`, `mosi`, `miso`, `cs#`
- Samplerate: `2M` is sufficient for typical SPI clock rates used in this repo
- Trigger: `cs#=f` (CS# falling edge) — CS# is active-low, so this marks the
  start of a transaction instead of idle bus
- Capture command template (fill in your LA channel wiring from `CONFIGS.md`):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -d fx2lafw \
    --channels <ch_mosi>=MOSI,<ch_sclk>=SCLK,<ch_miso>=MISO,<ch_cs>=CS# \
    --config samplerate=2M:captureratio=1 \
    --triggers CS#=f \
    --output-file spi.sr \
    --time <duration>
  ```
  `<duration>` is the approximate runtime of the test/example being probed —
  the trigger positions the capture at the transaction, `--time` just bounds
  the session.
- Analyze command (channel names come from the capture, no `-C` needed):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -i spi.sr -P spi:clk=SCLK:mosi=MOSI:miso=MISO:cs#=CS# -A spi
  ```

### UART

- Decoder: `uart` (built-in)
- Decoder channels: `rx`, `tx`
- Samplerate: `250k` is sufficient for typical UART baud rates
- Trigger: none — TXD and RXD are independent lines and either can send
  first, so there's no single edge that reliably marks "transaction start"
  the way a bus START condition or CS# does. Time-based capture only.
- Capture command template (fill in your LA channel wiring from `CONFIGS.md`):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -d fx2lafw \
    --channels <ch_tx>=TXD,<ch_rx>=RXD \
    --config samplerate=250k \
    --output-file uart.sr \
    --time <duration>
  ```
  `<duration>` is the approximate runtime of the test/example being probed.
- Analyze command (channel names come from the capture, no `-C` needed):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -i uart.sr -P uart:rx=RXD:tx=TXD -A uart
  ```

### SiPo

- Decoder: `sipo` (custom, `sigrok/sipo/`) — reads all pins directly, no
  transport decoder to stack on (`inputs = ['logic']`)
- Decoder channels: `ser_in`, `srck`, `rck` (required); `srclr`, `g`
  (optional)
- Samplerate: `2M` for now (fx2lafw only supports discrete rates — 20k, 25k,
  50k, 100k, 200k, 250k, 500k, 1M, 2M, 3M, 4M, 6M, 8M, 12M, 16M, 24M, 48M;
  `5M` is not one of them) — may be too slow for hardware SPI mode.
- Trigger: none — SRCK/RCK and the optional SRCLR/G lines are independent
  and any of them could toggle first depending on what the test does, so
  there's no single edge that reliably marks "activity start". Time-based
  capture only.
- Capture command template (fill in your LA channel wiring from `CONFIGS.md`):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -d fx2lafw \
    --channels <ch_ser_in>=SER_IN,<ch_srck>=SRCK,<ch_srclr>=SRCLR#,<ch_rck>=RCK,<ch_g>=G# \
    --config samplerate=2M \
    --output-file sipo.sr \
    --time <duration>
  ```
  `<duration>` is the approximate runtime of the test/example being probed.
- Analyze command (channel names come from the capture, no `-C` needed):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -i sipo.sr -P sipo:ser_in=SER_IN:srck=SRCK:rck=RCK:srclr=SRCLR#:g=G# -A sipo
  ```

### NeoPixel

- Decoder: `neopixel` (custom, `sigrok/neopixel/`) — reads DIN directly, no
  transport decoder to stack on (`inputs = ['logic']`); stack a chip decoder
  (`ws2812b`, `sk6812rgbw`) on top for chip-level bytes/pixels
- Decoder channels: `din`
- Samplerate: `6M` (nearest fx2lafw-supported rate to the ~5M needed to
  resolve the ~1.25 µs NZR bit timing accurately — see the SiPo entry above
  for the full supported-rate list)
- Trigger: `din=r` (DIN rising edge) — the line idles LOW between resets, so
  a rising edge marks the start of the first bit pulse
- Capture command template (fill in your LA channel wiring from `CONFIGS.md`):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -d fx2lafw \
    --channels <ch_din>=DIN \
    --config samplerate=6M:captureratio=1 \
    --triggers DIN=r \
    --output-file neo.sr \
    --time <duration>
  ```
  `<duration>` is the approximate runtime of the test/example being probed.
- Analyze command (channel names come from the capture, no `-C` needed):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -i neo.sr -P neopixel:din=DIN -A neopixel
  ```
- Stacked with a chip decoder, e.g. `ws2812b`:
  ```
  sigrok-cli -i neo.sr -P neopixel:din=DIN,ws2812b -A neopixel,ws2812b
  ```

### HX711

- Decoder: `hx711` (custom, `sigrok/hx711/`) — reads DOUT/PD_SCK directly,
  no transport decoder to stack on (`inputs = ['logic']`)
- Decoder channels: `dout`, `sck`
- Samplerate: `2M` — needed for the decoder's 60 µs power-down timeout
  detection to be accurate
- Trigger: `sck=f` (PD_SCK falling edge) — marks a clock pulse, so the
  capture begins on activity instead of idle (DOUT/PD_SCK both idle HIGH/LOW
  between conversions)
- Capture command template (fill in your LA channel wiring from `CONFIGS.md`):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -d fx2lafw \
    --channels <ch_dout>=DOUT,<ch_sck>=PD_SCK \
    --config samplerate=2M:captureratio=1 \
    --triggers PD_SCK=f \
    --output-file hx711.sr \
    --time <duration>
  ```
  `<duration>` is the approximate runtime of the test/example being probed.
- Analyze command (channel names come from the capture, no `-C` needed):
  ```
  sigrok-cli -i hx711.sr -P hx711:dout=DOUT:sck=PD_SCK -A hx711
  ```
